<div data-cmp-data-layer=3D"{&quot;richtext-81f3f20c06&quot;:{&quot;@type&q=
uot;:&quot;vanguard-retail-common/components/richtext/v1/richtext&quot;,&qu=
ot;repo:modifyDate&quot;:&quot;2025-01-28T17:05:30Z&quot;,&quot;xdm:text&qu=
ot;:&quot;&lt;h2&gt;&lt;span class=3D\&quot;cmp-richtext--fz-h3 cmp-richtex=
t--ff-mark cmp-richtext--fw-heavy\&quot;&gt;Realized gains vs. unrealized g=
ains&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;Gains that are &amp;quot;on paper&=
amp;quot; only are called &amp;quot;unrealized gains.&amp;quot; For example=
, if you bought a share for $10 and it's now worth $12, you have an unreali=
zed gain of $2. You won't pay any taxes until you sell the share.&lt;/p&gt;=
\r\n&lt;p&gt;Unrealized gains could be very important if you invest in fund=
s, however. When you buy shares of a &lt;a href=3D\&quot;#modal-mutual-fund=
\&quot;&gt;mutual fund&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=3D\&quot;#modal-ETFs\&quot;&=
gt;ETF (exchange-traded fund)&lt;/a&gt;, you're also &amp;quot;buying&amp;q=
uot; a proportional slice of any unrealized gains it has=E2=80=94and you'll=
 be subject to their eventual taxation. You may also owe taxes if the fund =
realizes a gain by selling a security for more than the original purchase p=
rice, even if you haven't sold any shares.&lt;br&gt;\r\n&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p=
&gt;&lt;a href=3D\&quot;/content/retail/public/us/en/investor-resources-edu=
cation/taxes/how-mutual-funds-etfs-are-taxed.html\&quot;&gt;Find out more a=
bout fund taxation&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&quot;}}" id=3D"richtext-81f3f20c=
06" class=3D"cmp-richtext ">
    <h2><span class=3D"cmp-richtext--fz-h3 cmp-richtext--ff-mark cmp-richte=
xt--fw-heavy">Realized gains vs. unrealized gains</span></h2>
<p>Gains that are "on paper" only are called "unrealized gains." For exampl=
e, if you bought a share for $10 and it's now worth $12, you have an unreal=
ized gain of $2. You won't pay any taxes until you sell the share.</p>
<p>Unrealized gains could be very important if you invest in funds, however=
. When you buy shares of a <a href=3D"https://investor.vanguard.com/investo=
r-resources-education/taxes/realized-capital-gains#modal-mutual-fund" data-=
initialized=3D"true">mutual fund</a> or <a href=3D"https://investor.vanguar=
d.com/investor-resources-education/taxes/realized-capital-gains#modal-ETFs"=
 data-initialized=3D"true">ETF (exchange-traded fund)</a>, you're also "buy=
ing" a proportional slice of any unrealized gains it has=E2=80=94and you'll=
 be subject to their eventual taxation. You may also owe taxes if the fund =
realizes a gain by selling a security for more than the original purchase p=
rice, even if you haven't sold any shares.<br>
</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://investor.vanguard.com/investor-resources-education/ta=
xes/how-mutual-funds-etfs-are-taxed">Find out more about fund taxation</a><=
/p>

